  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally obtained money appear legal by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems. Key legal elements typically include:\n\n1. Legal definitions usually involve three main stages:\n- Placement (introducing illegal funds into financial system)\n- Layering (concealing the source through complex transactions)\n- Integration (making funds appear legitimate)\n\n2. Common legal criteria include:\n- Knowingly conducting financial transactions with proceeds from illegal activities\n- Attempting to disguise the origin of illegally obtained funds\n- Intentionally hiding the source or ownership of criminal proceeds\n\n3. Most jurisdictions consider money laundering a criminal offense involving:\n- Drug trafficking proceeds\n- Fraud\n- Corruption\n- Organized crime revenues\n- Terrorist financing\n\n4. Legal approaches vary between countries, but generally require:\n- Proof of intent\n- Demonstrable connection to underlying criminal activity\n- Deliberate attempts to disguise funds' origins\n\n5. Penalties often include:\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n\nI want to be clear that while I can discuss this topic generally, I cannot provide specific legal advice about money laundering.",
